          "body": "The chapter's final three verses are the theological hinge. The men of Jabesh-gilead hear what the Philistines have done and rise — not because they receive a command, but because they remember. Their community exists because Saul rescued it. In 1 Samuel 11, when Nahash the Ammonite besieged Jabesh-gilead and threatened to gouge out every right eye (11:2), it was Saul's first act as king to muster Israel and deliver them (11:11). The men of Jabesh-gilead have not forgotten. They walk all night — risking Philistine territory, sacrificing safety — to retrieve the bodies of Saul and his sons from Beth-shan's wall. Then they burn the bodies (whether to prevent further desecration or in keeping with local practice is debated), bury the bones under the tamarisk tree, and fast seven days. This is *hesed* — covenantal loyalty that operates in the absence of obligation. No one has told them to do this. No king has commanded it. They act from memory. David will honor this memory explicitly in 2 Samuel 2:4-7."
