          "title": "The tamarisk tree — a burial and a bridge",
          "body": "The last image of 1 Samuel is bones buried under a tamarisk tree in Jabesh while the community fasts. The tamarisk (*eshel*) is mentioned only twice elsewhere in connection with Saul — he sat under a tamarisk tree on a high place at Gibeah when his men reported David had arrived (1 Sam. 22:6). It is the tree of Saul's kingship from its anxiety to its end. Now his bones rest under one. The burial under the tamarisk is quiet, unheroic, and permanent. The fast of seven days is the full mourning period — not a token. Jabesh does not minimize what it has lost. But the chapter does not end in despair. The reader of 1 Samuel knows what 2 Samuel will open with: David's lament over Saul and Jonathan (2 Sam. 1:17-27), and then the long, providential process of David's consolidation of the kingdom. The tamarisk tree is not the end of the story — it is the hinge between one anointed king and another."
