          "body": "1 Samuel opened with a barren woman praying in the tabernacle (1:1-18) and a corrupt priesthood desecrating the sacrifices (2:12-17). It closes with a fallen king desecrated by pagans and a loyal community burying what remains. The arc is long and dark, but not without hope. Hannah's prayer in 2:1-10 — which the narrator placed at the book's theological front — declared: 'The LORD will judge the ends of the earth; and He will give strength to His king, and will exalt the horn of His anointed' (2:10). That anointed king is not Saul. Saul is the negative proof — the king chosen by human standards (tall, handsome, from the right tribe) who failed by divine standards. The anointed whose horn God will exalt is the shepherd from Bethlehem who was already on the move in 1 Samuel 30, already acting with the *hesed* that Saul never mastered. Chapter 31 clears the stage. The story is not over; it is ready."
